---

In order to fix this:

- modify linux.py:Linux.sys_exit_group
- `error_code` is passed as the unsigned integer equivalent of what should be a signed int. We simply need to change the way the `error_code` is converted to a string in the logger.debug call and the `TerminateState` call

Currently, dynet do runtime checking on the forward/backward (dimension, input indices, etc.) at any circumstance. And the time consumption is non-trivial. I've tried blinding the LookupNode::forward by removing such checking (line: 257-258 in param-nodes.cc) and it led to less running time (8800+ ms to 8300+ ms on 1000000 lookups, code below).

It would be great to let the user decide whether performing runtime checking. In some circumstance, the user would be sure that their network's dimensions are correctly configured and everything is right with their data.

reference code:
```
  dynet::Model m;
  dynet::LookupParameter p_W = m.add_lookup_parameters(n_entries, { n_dim });
  for (unsigned i = 0; i < embeddings.size(); ++i) { p_W.initialize(i, embeddings[i]); }

  unsigned n_repeat = boost::lexical_cast<unsigned>(argv[2]);
  unsigned n_tests = boost::lexical_cast<unsigned>(argv[3]);
  unsigned n_batch = boost::lexical_cast<unsigned>(argv[4]);
  std::vector<std::vector<unsigned>> tests(n_tests, std::vector<unsigned>(n_batch));
  for (unsigned t = 0; t < n_tests; ++t) {
    for (unsigned b = 0; b < n_batch; ++b) { tests[t][b] = ((*dynet::rndeng)()) % n_entries; }
  }
  auto time_start = std::chrono::high_resolution_clock::now();
  unsigned t = 0;
  std::cerr << "start testing" << std::endl;
  for (unsigned repeat = 0; repeat < n_repeat; ++repeat) {
    dynet::ComputationGraph cg;
    dynet::expr::Expression emb = dynet::expr::lookup(cg, p_W, tests[t]);
    std::vector<float> v = dynet::as_vector(cg.get_value(emb));
    std::cout << v[0] << std::endl;
    t++;
    if (t == n_tests) { t = 0; }
  }
  auto eclipsed = std::chrono::high_resolution_clock::now() - time_start;
  std::cerr << "consume time: " << std::chrono::duration<double, std::milli>(eclipsed).count() << std::endl;
```

Hi, 

the version 1.17 of the Docker's API introduces the stats entry point.

It will be nice to have this new feature inside the docker-py lib.

The following method in the client.py file should do the job:

```
    def stats(self, container):
        if utils.compare_version('1.17', self._version) < 0:
            raise errors.InvalidVersion(
                'stats was only introduced in API version 1.17'
            )
        if isinstance(container, dict):
            container = container.get('Id')
        url = self._url("/containers/{0}/stats".format(container))
        return self._result(self._get(url), True)
```

@AndreasHeger may I request issue #268 be re-opened: 

I understand the point about invalid `reference_id`, but the -1 coordinate is returned for reads from the NOCOOR region, which is, by convention, referenced as '\*'. I would request that pysam return '*' for this. 

Thanks!

If I do a POST request with data containing a relationship:
`{
    "data": {
        "type": "comment",
        "attributes": {
            "text": "comment text"
        },
        "relationships": {
            "author": {
                "data": {
                    "id": "1 (invalid id)",
                    "type": "author"
                }
            }
        }
    }
}`
I got the following response:
`{
    "errors": [{
        "status": "400",
        "source": {"pointer": "/data/attributes/author"}, 
        "detail": "Error message"
    }]
}`
But would rather expect the following response:
`{
    "errors": [{
        "status": "400",
        "source": {"pointer": "/data/relationships/author"}, 
        "detail": "Error message"
    }]
}`
So the two responses are different when it comes to source/pointer.
Which version is the proper one? According to the specs the `pointer` should point to the associated entity in the request document.

